Good morning Grant,

Thank you so much for your email and for sharing the process document =
for my claim (C90306048) at 23 Mays Street, Devonport. I really =
appreciate your effort to outline the framework and the chance to work =
together on this. It=E2=80=99s great to see the team involved, and I=E2=80=
=99d love your guidance on how we can move forward smoothly.

I=E2=80=99ve looked over the process map and have a few thoughts to =
ensure we get this right, especially around safety and planning. I=E2=80=99=
ve heard from firefighters about significant fire damage and smoke =
exiting the roof=E2=80=94initially thought to originate there by =
Devonport Flagstaff=E2=80=94which has me concerned about the house=E2=80=99=
s condition.

Could we please consider the following adjustments?

Clarify Claim Scope: Is this the plan for both house and contents =
claims? If so, should it therefore be linked to both policy numbers to =
ensure all coverage is included?
Prioritize Health & Safety: I=E2=80=99d feel more comfortable if we =
scheduled independent assessments (electrical, structural, gas, =
moisture/mould) before any major work, alongside the July 9 asbestos =
survey. The master electrician=E2=80=99s finding that the property is =
uninhabitable due to electrical hazards is a key concern.
Assessment-Only Focus: As previously expressed, could we limit initial =
tasks to enabling damage assessment (e.g., securing the site, debris =
removal) rather than repairs (e.g., upstairs decontamination, curtain =
cleaning)? This would allow for a thorough evaluation and mutual =
agreement on remediation. The planned upstairs cleaning (July 21-25) =
feels premature for these reasons:
We need to assess damage before repair to preserve evidence.
If the gas unit (likely damaged) requires removal, the ceiling may need =
cutting, necessitating re-cleaning.
The electrician=E2=80=99s uninhabitable ruling requires electrical work =
first.
Firefighters switched off water (possibly gas?) and electricity, which =
must be assessed and remediated.
With 4 pets and hybrid work, noisy basement/deck/roof work makes living =
there untenable until completed.
Asbestos Survey Details: While I=E2=80=99m supportive of the July 9 =
survey, could you please share who will conduct it, the scope and tests =
involved, and how I can independently verify the results? Also, can the =
funding for this be covered under the claim preparation provision?
Structural Engineer Guidelines: I previously asked about guidelines for =
paying a structural engineer, as per the provision for claim =
preparation. Could you please provide these, as I believe an independent =
assessment should precede any repair work?
I=E2=80=99d be grateful if you could provide a revised plan with a =
written timeline for expert sign-offs and re-occupation only after =
safety is assured, preferably via email, by July 15, 2025. I=E2=80=99m =
really looking forward to working with you for a safe and fair outcome.

Kind regards,

Raffaella del Prete



> On 7 Jul 2025, at 5:31=E2=80=AFPM, Grant Metson =
<Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz> wrote:
>=20
> Good evening Rafaella,
> Thank you for taking the time to meet with me last week.
> As discussed, please find attached a process document which outlines =
the framework of how Tower Insurance will progress your claim.
> This is a framework only and the process will change, as we move =
through each step, given that findings and results will affect the next =
step in the process. This will be a live document that will gather =
detail as we progress.
> However, I do trust that this will give you some insight and knowledge =
to allow us to participate in the process together.
> I look forward to speaking with you soon.
> Please confirm back via email when you get a chance that you agree for =
Asset Restore to undertake the asbestos survey on the 9th =E2=80=93 as =
this is the first step in the process.
> Regards,
> Grant.=20
> =20
=EF=BF=BC=09
> Grant Metson
> Regional Manager - House Assessing
> Phone 021 744 288
